SIMPLE: meter
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: -meter
<hw>-me"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[L. <ets>metrum</ets> measure, or
the allied Gr. <?/. See <er>Meter</er> rhythm.]</ety> <def>A suffix
denoting <xex>that by which anything is measured</xex>; <as>as,
baro<ex>meter</ex>, chrono<ex>meter</ex>,
dynamo<ex>meter</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Meter
<hw>Me"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mete</er> to
measure.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, metes or
measures. See <er>Coal-meter</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An instrument for measuring, and usually for
recording automatically, the quantity measured.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Dry meter</b></col>, <cd>a gas meter having measuring
chambers, with flexible walls, which expand and contract like bellows
and measure the gas by filling and emptying.</cd> -- <col><b>Wet
meter</b></col>, <cd>a gas meter in which the revolution of a chambered
drum in water measures the gas passing through it.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Meter
<hw>Me"ter</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A line above or below a hanging net,
to which the net is attached in order to strengthen it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metre</ent>⟦br⟧
